  "prompt": "Can the sun melt snow in below freezing temperatures?",
  "response": "Yes, the sun can melt snow even when the air temperature is below freezing. This occurs because sunlight provides energy in the form of electromagnetic radiation, primarily visible and infrared light, which can be absorbed by the snow. Even if the air temperature is below freezing, the energy from the sun can raise the temperature of the snow itself to its melting point (0\u00b0C or 32\u00b0F), causing it to melt.\n\nHere\u2019s why this happens:\n\n1. **Direct Absorption of Solar Energy**: Snow can absorb sunlight, especially if it is dark or contains impurities like dirt or dust, which enhance absorption. This absorbed energy raises the snow's temperature.\n\n2. **Surface Melting**: Even if the air is cold, the surface of the snow can warm to 0\u00b0C and begin to melt, particularly on sunny days. The meltwater may then refreeze if the air temperature is still below freezing, forming ice.\n\n3. **Localized Warming**: Snow-covered surfaces can create microclimates where the temperature is slightly higher than the surrounding air due to solar heating. This localized warming can lead to melting.\n\nHowever, the process depends on factors like the intensity of sunlight, the albedo (reflectivity) of the snow, and air temperature. On a clear, sunny day, even in sub-freezing air, solar radiation can still cause snow to melt.",
